<subSubSection lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,334,930,956]" box="[189,334,930,956]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,930,956]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,930,956]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1398,975,1035]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
The sample, preserved dry, is a fragment collected from a sponge in the γ-stage (
<figureCitation box="[1114,1222,975,1001]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 17. Spheciospongia vagabunda (Ridley, 1884). A. Specimen PdO14 in situ. B. Big style. C. Small style. D. Spirasters." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978545" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978545/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
); this and other observed specimens, very common in the area, are attached by a broad base, with one or more large
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978545" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3978545" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978545/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" startId="30.[189,232,1966,1992]" targetBox="[191,1398,1067,1930]" targetPageId="30">
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1398,1966,2028]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,281,1966,1992]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 17.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley, 1884)" baseAuthorityName="Ridley" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[289,793,1966,1992]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="vagabunda">
<emphasis box="[289,612,1966,1992]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Spheciospongia vagabunda</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley" box="[628,784,1966,1992]" firstAuthor="Ridley" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="36 - 482" refId="ref21704" refString="Ridley S. O. 1884. Spongiida. Report on the Zoological Collections made in the Indo-Pacific Ocean during the Voyage of H. M. S. ' Alert', 1881 - 2: 36 - 482. British Museum of Natural History." type="journal article" year="1884">Ridley, 1884</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[804,825,1966,1992]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">A</emphasis>
. Specimen PdO14 
<emphasis box="[1052,1124,1967,1992]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">in situ</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1140,1160,1966,1992]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">B</emphasis>
. Big style. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1294,1315,1966,1992]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">C</emphasis>
. Small style. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[259,280,2002,2028]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">D</emphasis>
. Spirasters.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,267,327]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">vents and numerous digitate protuberances; it is brown, with a smooth surface and a cavernous body; the consistence is tough and incompressible.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1398,365,424]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">SKELETON. In the papillae, tylostyles are organized in palisade, in other parts the skeleton is more confused.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,461,621]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
SPICULES. Big and straight styles (
<figureCitation box="[571,676,461,488]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 17. Spheciospongia vagabunda (Ridley, 1884). A. Specimen PdO14 in situ. B. Big style. C. Small style. D. Spirasters." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978545" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978545/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
), 450–(536.8, 48.8)–620 ×9–(10.7, 1.5)– 
<quantity box="[1149,1225,461,488]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 µm</quantity>
, rare tylostyles with slightly pointed tips; smaller styles (
<figureCitation box="[663,767,495,521]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 17. Spheciospongia vagabunda (Ridley, 1884). A. Specimen PdO14 in situ. B. Big style. C. Small style. D. Spirasters." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978545" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978545/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
), 240–(284.3, 30.3)– 
<quantity box="[1009,1099,495,521]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="310.0">310 µm</quantity>
× 5–(5.7, 1.3)– 
<quantity box="[1273,1335,495,521]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 µm</quantity>
, with acerate tips and, sometimes, tylostyle modifications; spirasters (
<figureCitation box="[933,1039,528,554]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[191,1398,1067,1930]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 17. Spheciospongia vagabunda (Ridley, 1884). A. Specimen PdO14 in situ. B. Big style. C. Small style. D. Spirasters." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978545" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978545/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 17D</figureCitation>
) are stout, with average length of 
<quantity box="[223,323,561,588]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="12.5">12.5 µm</quantity>
and in several shapes: straight with spines at the extremities (amphiasters like), S-shaped wrapped with spines and slightly curved C-shaped spirasters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,303,658,684]" box="[189,303,658,684]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,658,684]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,658,684]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1398,703,763]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
This species is widely distributed in the Indo-Pacific Ocean. Already recorded in the area (Pulitzer- Finali 1993; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnes &amp; Bell" box="[339,576,736,763]" firstAuthor="Barnes" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="350 - 359" refId="ref19532" refString="Barnes D. K. A. &amp; Bell J. J. 2002. Coastal sponge communities of the West Indian Ocean: morphological, richness and diversity. African Journal of Ecology 40: 350 - 359. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1365 - 2028.2002.00388. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Barnes &amp; Bell 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Samaai" box="[588,812,736,762]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Samaai" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref21796" refString="Samaai T., Pillay R. &amp; Janson L. 2019. Shallow-water Demospongiae (Porifera) from Sodwana Bay, iSimangaliso Wetland Park, South Africa. Zootaxa 4587 (1): 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4587.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">
Samaai 
<emphasis box="[682,741,736,762]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
